    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a fair summary, but it seems like you're leaning heavily on the idea that it was a failure because of the instability. Some realists argue that the intervention was actually a success because it removed a volatile dictator and prevented a humanitarian catastrophe, even if the aftermath was messy. Is it fair to call it a 'failure' just because the transition wasn't smooth, or is there a more objective way to measure if a tactical intervention worked?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
